Sure! Below is a complete HTML file that simulates a random combination of NAND gates. This example includes embedded CSS and JavaScript for a simple web app that allows users to interact with NAND gates. The simulation will randomly generate a simple NAND gate circuit when the user clicks the "Generate Circuit" button.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>NAND Gate Circuit Simulator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            text-align: center;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        #circuit {
            margin: 20px auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 2px solid #333;
            border-radius: 10px;
            background-color: #fff;
            display: inline-block;
        }
        .gate {
            display: inline-block;
            margin: 10px;
            position: relative;
        }
        .nand {
            width: 60px;
            height: 30px;
            background-color: #ffcc00;
            border: 2px solid #333;
            border-radius: 15px;
            position: relative;
        }
        .inputs {
            position: absolute;
            left: -20px;
            top: 10px;
        }
        .output {
            position: absolute;
            right: -20px;
            top: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>NAND Gate Circuit Simulator</h1>
<button onclick="generateCircuit()">Generate Circuit</button>
<div id="circuit"></div>

<script>
    function generateCircuit() {
        const circuit = document.getElementById('circuit');
        circuit.innerHTML = ''; // Clear previous circuit

        const numGates = Math.floor(Math.random() * 5) + 1; // Random number of gates (1 to 5)
        for (let i = 0; i < numGates; i++) {
            const gate = document.createElement('div');
            gate.classList.add('gate');
            gate.innerHTML = `
                <div class="inputs"><strong>IN1</strong><br><strong>IN2</strong></div>
                <div class="nand">NAND</div>
                <div class="output"><strong>OUT</strong></div>
            `;
            circuit.appendChild(gate);
        }

        generateResult(numGates);
    }

    function generateResult(numGates) {
        // Generate a random output based on number of gates
        const result = Math.random() < 0.5 ? '0' : '1';
        alert(`The output of the circuit with ${numGates} gates is: ${result}`);
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Features of This Web App:
- The user can click the "Generate Circuit" button to create a random number of NAND gates (between 1 and 5).
- Each NAND gate is represented visually in a simple format.
- After generating the circuit, an alert displays a random output ("0" or "1") to simulate the result of the NAND gate logic.

### To Use This HTML:
1. Copy the code above into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `nand_gate_simulator.html`).
3. Open the saved file in a web browser to interact with the NAND gate simulator.

Feel free to modify the code to enhance its functionality or appearance!
